<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n53083b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53083b">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53083b"> 83(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> plinnyflowers, columellas, <small>Not cancelled</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53083b"><li>FW 354.26 </li><li><a href="../../flex/me/lexme.htm#n53083b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/me/l39me.htm#n53083b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53083b">MS BL 47480-105</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:193 <a name="mdd5" href="../../ff/fdra/mda.htm#med2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/me/med2.htm#n53083b">Draft: II.3&sect;5.2</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: These refer to the famous sentiment in Edgar Quinet&apos;s <cite>Introduction &agrave; la philosophie de l&apos;histoire de l&apos;humanit&eacute;</cite>, regarding the ephemeral nature of human grandeur when contrasted with the permanence of nature (typified by wild flowers), begining: &ldquo;<i>Aujourd&apos;hui, comme aux jours de Pline et de Columelle, la jacinthe se pla&icirc;t dans les Gaules, la pervenche en Illyrie &hellip;</i>&rdquo; &mdash; Today, as in the time of Pliny and of Columella, the hyacinth pleases itself in Gaul, the periwinkle in Illyria &hellip;. </mm> </dd></dl>
